      "content": "Besides temperature, several other factors can influence the rate of the Maillard reaction. pH, moisture levels, and the presence of other compounds can all impact the reaction.\n\npH plays a significant role in the Maillard reaction. The reaction is more rapid at lower pH values, typically below 4.5. This is because the acidity increases the availability of free radicals, which are necessary for the reaction to proceed. At higher pH values, the reaction is slower, as the increased pH reduces the availability of free radicals.\n\nMoisture levels also affect the Maillard reaction. Higher moisture levels can slow down the reaction, as excess water can dilute the concentration of reactants and reduce the rate of reaction. On the other hand, low moisture levels can accelerate the reaction, as the reduced water content allows for more efficient diffusion of reactants.\n\nThe presence of other compounds, such as salts, can also influence the Maillard reaction. For example, the addition of salt can increase the rate of the reaction by increasing the availability of free radicals. Conversely, the presence of certain compounds, such as antioxidants, can slow down the reaction by scavenging free radicals.\n\nIn terms of specific values, the Maillard reaction is often divided into three stages,",
